Oh, you can't turn
these sheets anymore.

12:03.498 --> 12:05.267
They've only got two sides.

12:05.334 --> 12:09.238
Polly, quit mooning over that
good-for-nothing songwriter.

12:09.304 --> 12:11.240
Where's that going to get you?

12:11.306 --> 12:13.142
Oh, he's wonderful, Trixie.

12:13.208 --> 12:14.876
Honey, he's a songwriter.

12:14.943 --> 12:18.013
So is Irving Berlin. What's
wrong about being a songwriter?

12:18.080 --> 12:20.115
How long have you
known him? Two weeks?

12:20.182 --> 12:21.816
What do you know about him?

12:21.883 --> 12:25.087
I knew everything I wanted
to know the minute I met him.

12:25.154 --> 12:27.156
[telephone rings]

12:27.222 --> 12:29.358
- Maybe it's Carol.
- O-o-oh.

12:30.459 --> 12:32.161
Hello.

12:32.227 --> 12:34.829
It's true.
It's really true.

12:34.896 --> 12:36.631
He's putting on a show.

12:36.698 --> 12:40.135
Oh, it's true.
Barney's putting on a show.

12:40.202 --> 12:41.970
We're coming right up
to the apartment.

12:42.037 --> 12:44.673
Be there in 10 minutes.
Phone all the girls.

12:44.739 --> 12:48.543
Phone Fay and Ruth and Mary
and Gwen. Phone them all.

12:48.610 --> 12:51.046
Tell them to come
right over to the apartment.

12:51.113 --> 12:53.248
He hasn't cast yet. No.

12:53.315 --> 12:55.417
Hurry. Don't lose him.

12:55.484 --> 12:57.119
- They're coming up.
- Who?

12:57.186 --> 13:00.155
Barney and Carol. Phone Fay,
all the girls. We're all set.

13:00.222 --> 13:02.591
You phone them. I'll dig up
the old sex appeal.

13:02.657 --> 13:05.260
I'll steam shovel
for the way I feel.

13:08.297 --> 13:09.898
Havermyer 48..

13:09.964 --> 13:12.934
Step on it, Polly. They ought
to be here any minute.

13:13.001 --> 13:14.869
(Polly)
'Almost ready.'

13:14.936 --> 13:19.108
Gosh. Do you think we're going
to have jobs again, earn money?

13:19.174 --> 13:21.143
I've been off
the gold standard so long.

13:21.210 --> 13:22.177
[knock on door]

13:22.244 --> 13:24.146
Oh, it's them!

13:25.514 --> 13:27.282
Come on in, Barney.
Meet the girls.

13:27.349 --> 13:29.784
- Hello, Mr. Hopkins.
- Howdy. Howdy.

13:29.851 --> 13:31.253
Hello, Mr. Hopkins.

13:32.887 --> 13:35.690
(Barney)
'I've seen that face before.'

13:35.757 --> 13:39.961
If it isn't Barney, good-old
smiling-big-hearted Barney.

13:40.028 --> 13:43.432
- You're putting on a show?
- Yes. I'm doing a show.

13:43.498 --> 13:46.168
You sound more enthusiastic.
That mean it's good?

13:46.235 --> 13:48.603
Good? It's the finest thing
I ever had.

13:48.670 --> 13:53.642
Come on over here and sit down
and tell us all about it.

13:53.708 --> 13:55.710
I figured it out
from every angle, kids.

13:55.777 --> 13:58.347
I can't see how it'd run
less than six months

13:58.413 --> 14:00.349
or gross less than
half a million.

14:00.415 --> 14:02.617
That's figuring on
30 grand a week.

14:02.684 --> 14:05.220
At the Broadhurst
we could do 40.

14:05.287 --> 14:07.122
We'll do 40 with this show.

14:07.189 --> 14:08.723
(Polly)
'Gosh!'

14:10.024 --> 14:12.026
- I remember you.
- Oh, do you?

14:12.093 --> 14:16.198
You were in the chorus. Someday,
you're coming out of the chorus.

14:16.265 --> 14:18.367
Oh, thank you,
Mr. Hopkins.

14:18.433 --> 14:20.068
Could you use
me too, Mr. Hopkins?

14:20.135 --> 14:23.505
Sure. I'm going to use
all the girls I used before.

14:23.572 --> 14:26.641
Carol here will be featured.

14:26.708 --> 14:29.144
And Trixie is comic.

14:29.211 --> 14:31.780
I got some ideas
for song numbers for you, honey

14:31.846 --> 14:34.883
that will drape them over their
seats. Something new, different.

14:34.949 --> 14:38.153
- What's the show about?
- It's all about the depression.

14:38.220 --> 14:40.021
We won't have to rehearse that.

14:40.088 --> 14:41.690
Now, it's my idea..

14:41.756 --> 14:43.692
[piano music]

14:46.961 --> 14:50.465
- Who is that playing?
- Oh, some palooka songwriter.

14:50.532 --> 14:52.534
I don't know that number.
What is it?

14:52.601 --> 14:54.503
It's his own.
He composes music.

14:54.569 --> 14:56.605
Shut the window.
Let's get on with this.

14:56.671 --> 14:59.241
Wait a minute.
That's not bad.

14:59.308 --> 15:01.876
Ask the fellow to come on over.

15:01.943 --> 15:04.246
- Oh, Brad!
- Hello.

15:04.313 --> 15:06.448
- Come on over, quick.
- Alright.

15:08.016 --> 15:12.554
That number's got a great feel
to it. The boy's got something.

15:12.621 --> 15:14.689
- Yeah, a piano.
- What's he done?

15:14.756 --> 15:17.959
He hasn't had a chance
to do anything yet, Mr. Hopkins.

15:18.026 --> 15:20.695
But he has genius.

15:20.762 --> 15:23.164
Well, the show business
could stand a little genius.

15:23.232 --> 15:24.766
[knock on door]

15:24.833 --> 15:27.101
Barney, what's the idea
wasting time with a genius

15:27.168 --> 15:29.738
when there's hard-working girls
like us to worry about?

15:32.173 --> 15:35.610
- What is it, honey?
- I want you to meet somebody.

15:35.677 --> 15:38.680
This is Brad Roberts.
Mr. Hopkins is our producer.

15:38.747 --> 15:40.682
Never mind that.
Sit down and play.

15:40.749 --> 15:42.684
- Play what?
- That number you were playing.

15:42.751 --> 15:45.887
- But I--
- It's okay. We're friends.

15:45.954 --> 15:49.090
- Go on, Brad.
- Well, alright.

15:49.157 --> 15:51.293
Oh, I beg your pardon.

15:52.627 --> 15:54.329
Say, what's this
all about, anyway?

15:54.396 --> 15:57.165
Go ahead and play.
Sing it if you got words.

15:57.232 --> 15:59.301
Alright.
Here goes.

16:02.437 --> 16:07.542
* I've got to sing
a torch song *

16:07.609 --> 16:10.679
* For that's the way I feel *

16:10.745 --> 16:16.485
* When I feel a thing
then I can sing *

16:17.452 --> 16:21.490
* It must be real

16:22.857 --> 16:28.029
* I couldn't sing a gay song *

16:28.096 --> 16:31.232
* It wouldn't be sincere *

16:31.300 --> 16:36.805
* I could never croon
a happy tune *

16:38.440 --> 16:42.344
* Without a tear

16:42.411 --> 16:46.815
* I have my dreams
but one by one *

16:46.881 --> 16:51.320
* They vanish in the sky *

16:51.386 --> 16:54.356
* I try to smile

16:54.423 --> 16:57.025
* And face the sun

16:57.091 --> 17:00.862
* But romance passes by

17:03.865 --> 17:09.103
* I've got to sing
a torch song *

17:09.170 --> 17:12.574
* To someone far apart *

17:12.641 --> 17:19.280
* For the torch I bear
is burning there *

17:21.450 --> 17:28.457
* Right in my heart *

17:30.258 --> 17:32.894
That's great! I like it.
Have you got anything else?

17:32.961 --> 17:36.565
- Yes. A couple of things.
- Well, play them. Play them.

17:40.802 --> 17:42.504
[knock on door]

17:46.007 --> 17:49.411
Oh, hello, Mr. Hopkins.
It's charming to see you again.

17:50.845 --> 17:53.014
Sit down, sit down.

17:54.949 --> 17:57.652
I don't like that, son.
It's too dull.

17:57.719 --> 18:00.622
Is this a piano lesson?
Are we gonna about this show?

18:00.689 --> 18:03.625
Shh, shh! Say, have you
got something

18:03.692 --> 18:06.260
with kind of a march effect,
march rhythm to it?

18:06.327 --> 18:08.597
Yes. I have something
about a forgotten man

18:08.663 --> 18:10.599
but I don't have the words yet.

18:10.665 --> 18:12.767
Well, play it.
Play it.

18:12.834 --> 18:15.003
I just got the idea
for it last night.

18:15.069 --> 18:18.072
I was down on Times Square
watching those men in bread line

18:18.139 --> 18:20.609
standing in the rain, waiting
for coffee and doughnuts.

18:20.675 --> 18:23.211
'Men out of a job
around a soup kitchen.'

18:23.277 --> 18:24.946
Stop!

18:25.013 --> 18:27.048
Go on. That's it.

18:27.115 --> 18:29.317
That's what this show's
about. The depression.

18:29.384 --> 18:31.420
Men marching,
marching in the rain.

18:31.486 --> 18:34.856
Doughnuts and crullers.
Men marching, marching.

18:34.923 --> 18:37.526
Jobs, jobs,
and in the background

18:37.592 --> 18:39.428
Carol, the spirit
of the depression.

18:39.494 --> 18:40.862
A blues song.

18:40.929 --> 18:44.533
No, not a blues song
but a wailing, a wailing.

18:44.599 --> 18:47.402
And this gorgeous woman
singing this song

18:47.469 --> 18:48.903
that will tear their hearts out.

18:48.970 --> 18:52.507
The big parade.
The big parade of tears.

18:52.574 --> 18:55.410
That's it! That's it!
Work on it! Work on it!

18:55.477 --> 18:58.980
- I'd like to do a specialty.
- Sit down. You'll do blackout.

19:01.049 --> 19:03.752
I'll cancel my contract with
Warren and Dubin. They're out.

19:03.818 --> 19:07.021
I want you to write the music
for this show and the lyrics.

19:07.088 --> 19:09.724
- Can you write lyrics?
- You bet he can.

19:11.192 --> 19:14.596
I got it all figured out. I want
your stuff, son. It's great.

19:14.663 --> 19:16.598
I definitely want it.

19:16.665 --> 19:19.367
Mr. Hopkins, you can have it...
on one condition.

19:19.434 --> 19:20.935
Yeah?

19:21.002 --> 19:24.272
If Ms. Parker, Polly has
a principal part in the show.

19:24.338 --> 19:26.908
She's helped me a lot
and she's really great herself.

19:26.975 --> 19:29.377
You're telling me?
I'm telling you.

19:29.444 --> 19:31.179
I'll tell you
something else, too.

19:31.245 --> 19:34.449
You got a swell voice
and a great personality.

19:34.516 --> 19:36.851
You're different.
You got class.

19:36.918 --> 19:39.053
I want you to sing in this show.

19:39.120 --> 19:41.289
Thanks a lot
but that's impossible.

19:41.355 --> 19:45.627
Listen, you and Polly would make
a swell team like the astaires.

19:45.694 --> 19:47.662
You'd be a knockout
for the mush interest.

19:47.729 --> 19:49.397
I'm sorry, but it's impossible.

19:49.464 --> 19:50.832
But Brad, why not?

19:50.899 --> 19:52.867
I can't, honey,
for a lot of reasons.

19:52.934 --> 19:56.771
Let me get in. Isn't there going
to be any comedy in this show?

19:56.838 --> 19:59.841
Plenty. The gay side,
the hard-boiled side

19:59.908 --> 20:02.343
the cynical and funny
side of the depression.

20:02.410 --> 20:05.113
I'll make them laugh at you
starving to death, honey.

20:05.179 --> 20:07.148
It'll be the funniest
thing you ever did.

20:07.215 --> 20:10.752
- You ever see me ride a pony?
- When do rehearsals begin?

20:10.819 --> 20:12.921
- Rehearsals?
- Uh-huh.

20:13.988 --> 20:16.224
- When I get the money.
- Get the money?

20:16.290 --> 20:17.826
(all)
Money?

20:17.892 --> 20:21.696
That's always the way it is.
I got the show, music, cast.

20:21.763 --> 20:24.198
And the theater,
all raring to go.

20:24.265 --> 20:26.935
And it's the old,
old story, money.

20:27.001 --> 20:30.171
- No money at all?
- Not even the old shoestring.

20:30.238 --> 20:33.007
- But you-you let us think--
- What did I let you think?

20:33.074 --> 20:36.144
I told you I had
a great show and I have.

20:36.210 --> 20:37.946
But you said it was all set.

20:38.012 --> 20:40.314
It is set. It's been set
for six months.

20:40.381 --> 20:43.952
Every time I get an angel to put
the bankroll, something happens.

20:44.018 --> 20:47.589
'I had one yesterday. Only
today, he came to me and said'

20:47.656 --> 20:50.024
he and his wife,
who was suing him for divorce

20:50.091 --> 20:52.060
had become reconciled,
and she didn't want him

20:52.126 --> 20:54.262
fooling around
in the show business

20:54.328 --> 20:56.130
and here I am, holding the bag.

20:56.197 --> 20:59.067
You've got your nerve, Barney.
What about these girls?

20:59.133 --> 21:01.736
They've given up jobs
because you said..

21:01.803 --> 21:03.572
Oh, you ought to be
ashamed of yourself.

21:03.638 --> 21:06.908
Gee, it's tough enough without
you making mugs out of us.

21:06.975 --> 21:08.977
We counted on this, all of us.

21:09.043 --> 21:11.813
Wait a minute, kids.
I'm not going to let you down.

21:11.880 --> 21:13.882
I've got other irons
in the fire.

21:13.948 --> 21:16.651
Two men are due here
tomorrow from out of town

21:16.718 --> 21:18.252
Texas. Cattle.

21:18.319 --> 21:19.721
Texas. Cattle.

21:19.788 --> 21:22.156
How can they sell cattle?
Who eats meat anymore?

21:22.223 --> 21:24.425
All I can say is..

21:24.492 --> 21:26.027
How much do you need?

21:26.094 --> 21:27.428
$50,000.

21:27.495 --> 21:31.099
There isn't $50,000 in the world
not to put a show on with.

21:31.165 --> 21:35.203
Alright, then, who needs 50,000?
Make it 40, 25.

21:35.269 --> 21:37.639
If I wanted to chisel
and I know how

21:37.706 --> 21:40.575
I could do it for 15, but..

21:40.642 --> 21:42.744
I'll advance you 15.

21:44.212 --> 21:47.215
What does he use? I'll smoke it
too. Quit joking, will you?

21:47.281 --> 21:50.084
It isn't smart to make gags
when girls are starving.

21:50.151 --> 21:52.553
This is too serious a matter to
all.

21:52.621 --> 21:54.623
Honey, I'll be glad to do it.

21:54.689 --> 21:56.324
Where can you get 15 grand?

21:56.390 --> 22:00.094
'He means real money
not streetcar transfers.'

22:00.161 --> 22:02.363
Remember, one condition
Polly's featured.

22:02.430 --> 22:04.565
Anything you say.

22:07.836 --> 22:11.072
No. I can't give you a check...
for certain reasons.

22:11.139 --> 22:13.307
I'll give you cash tomorrow.
Is that all right?

22:13.374 --> 22:16.911
- Ha! You fell for it, Barney.
- He did. He fell for it.

22:16.978 --> 22:18.913
That's what's commonly
known as a gag.

22:18.980 --> 22:22.583
It's not a gag. I mean it.
I'll be in your office at 10:30.

22:22.651 --> 22:26.254
You have my word for it. I'll go
work on that number a little.

22:26.320 --> 22:28.790
I'll see you later.
Goodbye, honey.

22:39.668 --> 22:41.135
Brad!

22:41.202 --> 22:42.771
Yes?

22:46.607 --> 22:49.010
- Brad, this is cruel.
- What, honey?

22:49.077 --> 22:51.079
To kid about a thing like this.

22:51.145 --> 22:53.114
I'm not kidding.
I'll give him the money.

22:53.181 --> 22:56.050
He'll have it in his office
at 10:30 tomorrow morning.

22:56.117 --> 22:59.253
Where are you going
to get $15,000?

22:59.320 --> 23:01.555
Well, honey,
I'll tell you, I'm..

23:01.622 --> 23:05.994
See this ring? I give it
a twist, make a wish, presto.

23:06.060 --> 23:07.395
Oh, Brad.

23:07.461 --> 23:10.098
Oh, trust me, will you,
honey? And I'm not joking.

23:10.164 --> 23:12.533
Well, that's just the trouble.
I do trust you.

23:12.600 --> 23:14.002
- Oh, honey.
- What?

23:14.068 --> 23:15.670
No. I won't
say it yet.

23:15.737 --> 23:19.741
I have an idea, I want to get
to the piano before I lose it.

23:19.808 --> 23:21.943
See you later, huh?

23:37.591 --> 23:41.462
He meant it. Really he did.
I'd stake my life on it.

23:41.529 --> 23:43.631
Faith, hope, and charity.

23:43.698 --> 23:47.235
You have faith, Barney hopes
and we all need charity.

23:50.171 --> 23:52.106
[piano music]

23:57.846 --> 23:59.948
Wait a minute.

24:00.514 --> 24:01.950
Listen.

24:03.151 --> 24:06.087
He's got it, just what I want.

24:06.154 --> 24:10.124
Don't you hear
that wailing, wailing?

24:10.191 --> 24:13.828
Men marching, marching,
marching in the rain.

24:13.895 --> 24:16.697
Jobs. Jobs.

24:17.631 --> 24:19.934
Gee, don't it get you?

24:47.695 --> 24:49.197
Well?

24:49.263 --> 24:51.532
There's no answer
at Mr. Roberts' apartment.

24:51.599 --> 24:53.367
Trixie can say, "I told you so"

24:53.434 --> 24:55.736
but I won't.
It hurts too much.

24:55.804 --> 24:57.238
[door slams]

24:58.472 --> 25:00.141
Come in, come in.

25:00.208 --> 25:04.012
Gigolo Eddie, always shows up
at the wrong time.

25:04.078 --> 25:07.281
Hello, Barney. I heard you got
some dough to open the show.

25:07.348 --> 25:10.819
Thought you might want to
celebrate. Fresh off the boat.

25:10.885 --> 25:12.320
You heard wrong.

25:12.386 --> 25:15.389
Pull up a coffin and lie down
with the rest of us.

25:15.456 --> 25:19.560
Business is so tough that nobody
even wants to owe me anymore.

25:19.627 --> 25:20.895
You can go.

25:20.962 --> 25:22.897
But you hired me for the day!

25:22.964 --> 25:25.099
I thought I was gonna
need a secretary.

25:25.166 --> 25:29.103
You will pay me for the day
or I'll complain to the agency.

25:29.170 --> 25:32.306
I wish there was somebody
I could complain to.

25:43.451 --> 25:47.155
- Who are you?
- The Kentucky Hill Billies.

25:47.221 --> 25:48.089
Who?

25:48.156 --> 25:50.191
The Kentucky Hill Billies.
Singing.

25:50.258 --> 25:51.192
Dancing.

25:51.259 --> 25:53.061
- Music.
- Wisecracks.

25:53.127 --> 25:56.030
- Know your old Kentucky home?
- You said it.

25:56.097 --> 25:59.233
Scram back there. Your old
mammy's waiting for you.

25:59.300 --> 26:00.835
We get it.

26:00.902 --> 26:03.237
[speaking foreign language]

26:05.706 --> 26:07.275
I better lock this joint

26:07.341 --> 26:10.544
before the acrobats and midgets
start flocking in.

26:13.747 --> 26:15.683
Good morning.
You're early.

26:15.749 --> 26:17.518
I'm sorry I kept
you all waiting.

26:17.585 --> 26:21.189
I got a new idea for a number
and lost track. Got a piano?

26:21.255 --> 26:23.124
Listen, kid, I'm
the comedian around here.

26:23.191 --> 26:25.159
We've had enough
of your gags. Not funny.

26:25.226 --> 26:28.096
Please stop it, Brad.
There's a limit to everything.

26:28.162 --> 26:30.531
I'm locking up. Get out
of here, all of you.

26:30.598 --> 26:32.800
- Don't you want the money?
- Don't kid me!

26:32.867 --> 26:35.103
There you are.
$15,000 cash.

26:35.169 --> 26:37.338
Brad, I knew you were
on the level.

26:37.405 --> 26:38.172
[cheering]

26:38.239 --> 26:40.674
Rehearsals start at 9 a.m.

26:40.741 --> 26:42.543
Fresh off the boat.

26:44.946 --> 26:47.648
* Pettin' in the park *
* Bad boy

26:47.715 --> 26:50.084
* Pettin' in the park *
Bad girl *

26:50.151 --> 26:52.921
* First you pet a little
Let up a little *

26:52.987 --> 26:55.189
* And then you get
a little kiss *

26:55.256 --> 26:56.824
* Pettin' on the sly *

26:56.891 --> 26:58.092
* Oh my

26:58.159 --> 27:00.494
* Act a little shy, oh, why? *

27:00.561 --> 27:03.131
* Struggle just a little
Then hug a little *

27:03.197 --> 27:05.166
* And cuddle up
and whisper this *

27:05.233 --> 27:08.136
* Come on, I've been
waiting long *

27:08.202 --> 27:09.803
(Brad)
Wait a minute! Wait a minute.

27:09.870 --> 27:12.873
Oh, Gordon, you got to put
some life into that song.

27:12.941 --> 27:14.442
Yeah?

27:14.508 --> 27:17.678
Sing it with pep and feeling!
You got it wrong. Listen.

27:17.745 --> 27:21.882
Play the first chorus. Here's
the way it goes. Come on.

27:21.950 --> 27:24.018
* Pettin' in the park, bad boy *

27:24.085 --> 27:26.520
* Pettin' in the park,
bad girl *

27:26.587 --> 27:29.357
* First you pet a little
Let up a little *

27:29.423 --> 27:31.559
* Then you get a little kiss *

27:31.625 --> 27:34.062
* Pettin' on the sly oh, my *

27:34.128 --> 27:36.164
* Act a little shy, oh, why? *

27:36.230 --> 27:38.832
* Struggle just a little
Then hug a little *

27:38.899 --> 27:40.668
* Cuddle up and whisper this *

27:40.734 --> 27:43.304
* Come on, I've been
waiting long *

27:43.371 --> 27:45.139
* Why don't we get started? *

27:45.206 --> 27:47.375
Wait a minute.
Wait a minute.

27:47.441 --> 27:49.443
What am I doing that's so wrong?

27:49.510 --> 27:51.245
You do this in the middle.

27:51.312 --> 27:53.281
[slowly]
* Come on, I've
been waiting *

27:53.347 --> 27:55.116
That's not the melody.
Here it is.

27:55.183 --> 27:57.318
* Come on, I've been
waiting long *

27:57.385 --> 27:59.420
* Why don't we get started? *

27:59.487 --> 28:01.289
Alright.
Alright.

28:01.355 --> 28:03.291
Now let me tell you something.

28:03.357 --> 28:05.226
I've been a juvenile
for 18 years

28:05.293 --> 28:07.628
and you're going
to tell me how to sing?

28:07.695 --> 28:10.965
Come on, fellows, let me down.
I want a glass of water.

28:11.032 --> 28:13.334
Come on. Show me
that dance chorus.

28:13.401 --> 28:16.904
Snap into it. Hit it, Malcolm.
Come on. Let's go.

28:16.971 --> 28:19.373
Brad, why don't you
do this part?

28:19.440 --> 28:21.409
You've got it over Gordon
like a tent.

28:21.475 --> 28:23.411
Reconsider. Give your
songs a break.

28:23.477 --> 28:27.481
- I told you. I can't do it.
- But you don't tell me why.

28:33.754 --> 28:36.057
You've got a voice,
you've got personality

28:36.124 --> 28:38.092
you can do it,
but you won't. Why?

28:38.159 --> 28:40.928
Will you let it go at that
once and for all?

28:40.995 --> 28:43.031
No public appearances.

28:47.068 --> 28:49.237
- Hi, sweets.
- Hello.

28:53.374 --> 28:56.010
You've got quite a yen
for that boy, haven't you?

28:56.077 --> 28:58.479
Oh, I, uh, I like him,
of course.

28:58.546 --> 29:02.016
There's something funny about
him, something very mysterious.

29:02.083 --> 29:04.252
Did he tell you
where he got 15,000?

29:04.318 --> 29:07.988
And why he lives on $25 a week
but can get that much money?

29:08.056 --> 29:11.559
Look, a Toronto bank clerk
took $20,000 from bank

29:11.625 --> 29:13.127
and disappeared.

29:13.194 --> 29:14.528
I can read.

29:14.595 --> 29:16.764
That's quite a coincidence,
I should say.

29:16.830 --> 29:18.299
What is?

29:18.366 --> 29:20.801
"New York police asked to
check out Broadway nightspots."

29:20.868 --> 29:24.272
And here's the description.
"5'9", dark hair."

29:24.338 --> 29:25.773
That could describe anybody.

29:25.839 --> 29:28.642
It couldn't describe me,
and it describes him.

29:28.709 --> 29:31.079
He's about 5'9"
and has got dark hair.

29:31.145 --> 29:33.081
And where did he get that cash?

29:33.147 --> 29:34.748
Don't be ridiculous, Trixie.

29:34.815 --> 29:36.884
You're letting your imagination
run away with you.

29:36.950 --> 29:40.554
I don't wanna see you with a guy
who will get you into trouble.

29:40.621 --> 29:42.890
Oh, I know,
but-but I'm sure.

29:42.956 --> 29:44.658
What do you know about him?

29:44.725 --> 29:47.095
Does he ever talk
about himself or his family?

29:47.161 --> 29:49.997
Do you remember he wouldn't
give Barney a check?

29:50.064 --> 29:51.965
And he won't play Gordon's part.

29:52.032 --> 29:55.469
Why? Because he's afraid
that newspaper..

30:02.110 --> 30:05.246
Don't talk and don't
come back here. Do you promise?

30:05.313 --> 30:07.448
I said I wouldn't, didn't I?

30:07.515 --> 30:09.317
So long.

30:10.751 --> 30:13.254
Don't say anything to anyone,
will you, Trixie?

30:39.012 --> 30:40.448
(male #4)
'Whoa!'

30:41.782 --> 30:44.418
'Hurry, will you?
Cut her down.'

30:44.485 --> 30:46.987
(male #5)
'On stage!'

30:47.054 --> 30:48.822
'Stage ready.
Come on.'

30:48.889 --> 30:50.824
On stage!

30:59.200 --> 31:03.604
This stuff is just as good
to rub with as it is to drink.

31:03.671 --> 31:04.938
It penetrates.

31:05.005 --> 31:06.974
Now show me the spot.

31:07.040 --> 31:10.678
It's been an hour,
and he says, "Show me the spot."

31:10.744 --> 31:12.180
Ow!

31:12.246 --> 31:14.515
- What's this?
- It's his lumbago.

31:14.582 --> 31:17.185
- Get up.
- I can't, I tell you.

31:17.251 --> 31:19.153
Oh, you can't get up, can't you?

31:19.220 --> 31:22.156
Oh! Don't, please!
Oh, don't!

31:22.223 --> 31:24.158
Straighten up,
you permanent juvenile.

31:24.225 --> 31:26.093
Oh! I can't,
I tell you. I can't.

31:26.160 --> 31:29.163
You don't suppose you're going
out and singing a love song

31:29.230 --> 31:31.165
with your back
doubled up, do you?

31:31.232 --> 31:33.867
What kind of song
do you think this is?

31:33.934 --> 31:35.169
You've got to straighten up!

31:35.236 --> 31:37.070
You've got to stop being a baby.

31:37.137 --> 31:39.773
Mind over matter.
Mind over matter.

31:39.840 --> 31:41.775
Oh. Oh!

31:41.842 --> 31:43.277
I can't, I tell you.

31:43.344 --> 31:46.414
I got a show. I spent weeks
and months getting a show.

31:46.480 --> 31:48.616
I've worked!
I've slaved!

31:48.682 --> 31:50.150
Opening night!

31:50.218 --> 31:53.053
We open tonight
and he's got lumbago.

31:53.120 --> 31:55.289
Go out and announce
the show is postponed.

31:55.356 --> 31:56.790
Give them their money back.

31:56.857 --> 32:00.194
Tell them our juvenile man's
dying of old age.

32:01.795 --> 32:05.599
Listen, kid, now it's up to you.
You've got to go in his place.

32:05.666 --> 32:07.000
I can't.

32:07.067 --> 32:10.804
Why? The curtain's going up.
The show's going on.

32:10.871 --> 32:12.840
Your girl's in it.
Your music's in it.

32:12.906 --> 32:15.343
Your money's in it!
You've got to do it.

32:15.409 --> 32:17.778
- There's a reason.
- There can't be!

32:17.845 --> 32:19.780
- Alright.
- What's your reason?

32:19.847 --> 32:22.015
Listen, I don't care
if you go to jail.

32:22.082 --> 32:24.652
You ought to forget about
yourself and do this anyway.

32:24.718 --> 32:27.488
You know what it means
if this show doesn't go on.

32:27.555 --> 32:30.758
What it means to the girls,
those poor kids who gave up jobs

32:30.824 --> 32:32.860
and won't be able
to find other ones?

32:32.926 --> 32:36.330
They've been living on nothing,
starving themselves for weeks

32:36.397 --> 32:38.966
hoping for this show
to go on and be a success.

32:39.032 --> 32:41.669
They're counting on you.
You can't let them down.

32:41.735 --> 32:44.104
If you do...God knows
what will happen to them.

32:44.171 --> 32:47.174
They'll have to do things I
wouldn't want on my conscience

32:47.241 --> 32:48.642
and it'll be on yours.

32:48.709 --> 32:51.479
Now you can go out
and sing Gordon's part.

32:51.545 --> 32:54.915
If you don't, I don't care
what your reason is!

32:54.982 --> 32:57.385
She's right, Brad.

32:57.451 --> 32:59.620
I hadn't thought
about it in that way.

32:59.687 --> 33:03.090
- Yes, of course. I'll do it.
- Great, kid! I knew you would.

33:03.156 --> 33:06.460
Get him a dressing room.
He's not on for seven minutes.

33:06.527 --> 33:09.229
We won't have to hold
the curtain. Come on!

33:12.900 --> 33:15.403
Get him ready!

33:15.469 --> 33:17.605
If anything happens
to him now, we're responsible.

33:17.671 --> 33:20.240
There's more to him than
I thought. He has nerve.

33:20.308 --> 33:22.242
He belongs in the show business.

33:22.310 --> 33:24.278
He's risking going
to prison for us.

33:24.345 --> 33:28.248
If he goes to prison for this,
I'll visit him. I swear I will.

33:28.316 --> 33:31.285
I want to tell him that
I know what it means.

33:32.720 --> 33:34.187
- Brad?
- 'Hello.'

33:34.254 --> 33:37.458
Put your ear to the door.
I want to whisper to you.

33:37.525 --> 33:39.159
(Brad)
'Alright.'

33:39.226 --> 33:41.995
Brad, it's wonderful of you
to take this chance tonight.

33:42.062 --> 33:43.731
It's-it's courageous.

33:43.797 --> 33:45.733
(Brad)
'Oh, it's not
courageous, exactly.'

33:45.799 --> 33:48.268
'But how do you know?
