and wants to know my price.'

50:32.138 --> 50:34.006
Well, have you told him, Polly?

50:34.073 --> 50:36.443
I was gonna tell him
where to head in.

50:36.509 --> 50:39.312
Oh, I wouldn't be too hasty.

50:39.379 --> 50:41.314
I'd at least discuss it further.

50:41.381 --> 50:42.982
After all,
we're grown up, sensible.

50:43.049 --> 50:46.252
You're a woman of the world.
I'm a man of the world.

50:46.319 --> 50:48.421
Oh, we ought to
have a conference.

50:48.488 --> 50:50.490
Isn't that what businessmen
always have

50:50.557 --> 50:52.759
when they're away
from home? Conferences?

50:52.825 --> 50:54.961
I know a new speakie!
It just opened.

50:55.027 --> 50:57.597
Their liquor is good,
and do I know good liquor.

50:57.664 --> 50:59.432
It's right around the corner.

50:59.499 --> 51:02.535
We'll be ready in two minutes.
I'll just slip into something.

51:02.602 --> 51:05.438
- Oh, I beg your pardon.
- What's that?

51:05.505 --> 51:07.540
My slip. Come along,
Polly, dear.

51:07.607 --> 51:09.976
Let's not keep them waiting.

51:10.042 --> 51:14.747
Oh, here's something
for you to read

51:14.814 --> 51:16.816
Mr. Bradford.

51:16.883 --> 51:22.321
And...here are some pictures
for you to look at.

51:22.389 --> 51:26.959
Now, you amuse yourselves, won't
you? We'll just be two minutes.

51:27.026 --> 51:28.428
Fanny.

51:35.768 --> 51:38.270
Peabody, you're disgusting.

51:38.337 --> 51:42.208
- I'm going to kick them out!
- After he called you parasite?

51:42.274 --> 51:45.277
What's a parasite?
You'd better resent it.

51:45.344 --> 51:47.880
He did get under
my skin. Stuck-up snob.

51:47.947 --> 51:49.849
They've had their turn.
Let's have ours.

51:49.916 --> 51:53.352
We'll take them for a ride. Use
the bathroom I'll use the phone.

51:53.420 --> 51:55.722
Uh, Endicott 2..

51:59.726 --> 52:01.628
Hello, Madam Minnie?

52:01.694 --> 52:03.696
This is Trixie Lorraine.

52:03.763 --> 52:06.265
Say, you know the hat with the..

52:06.332 --> 52:07.634
Yeah.

52:07.700 --> 52:09.368
No, no.

52:09.436 --> 52:12.004
The expensive one.

52:21.648 --> 52:23.850
[door buzzer]

52:26.753 --> 52:28.888
[buzzing continues]

52:33.192 --> 52:35.495
Oh, did the buzzer buzz?

52:38.130 --> 52:40.867
Huh! Oh, what's that?

52:40.933 --> 52:44.537
A COD for Ms. Polly Parker.
Seventy five bucks.

52:44.604 --> 52:47.874
Seventy five bucks just
for a little hat?

52:50.209 --> 52:54.847
Oh-h-h, but she'll look
adorable in that, won't she?

52:54.914 --> 52:56.816
Yes, she will.

52:56.883 --> 52:59.619
Now let me see.
What does COD mean?

53:00.853 --> 53:03.523
That means you've got
to pay for it.

53:03.590 --> 53:06.526
Oh, how inconvenient.

53:06.593 --> 53:08.695
Well, you'll
have to take it back.

53:08.761 --> 53:11.464
Oh, dear. She'll be
in such a bad mood.

53:11.531 --> 53:13.099
- Who will?
- Polly.

53:13.165 --> 53:16.903
She wanted to wear that hat when
she went for lunch with you.

53:16.969 --> 53:19.438
'Oh, dear. When she doesn't
get what she wants.'

53:19.506 --> 53:20.973
You just don't know Polly.

53:21.040 --> 53:23.342
Oh, so disagreeable.
She's no fun at all.

53:23.409 --> 53:24.677
Just sits there.

53:24.744 --> 53:26.913
She won't agree
to anything you say.

53:26.979 --> 53:29.482
She probably won't even
want to go with us.

53:29.549 --> 53:32.619
We three will just
have to go alone.

53:33.820 --> 53:37.289
There you are, boy.
Take it back.

53:37.356 --> 53:39.559
Here, wait a minute.

53:39.626 --> 53:43.129
- How much is it?
- Seventy five bucks.

53:43.195 --> 53:45.865
Seventy five...for a hat?

53:45.932 --> 53:48.535
Sure, that's what
the ticket calls for.

53:53.172 --> 53:55.107
Here.

53:55.174 --> 53:57.577
- Leave the hat.
- You darling man.

53:57.644 --> 54:00.613
Polly's just going
to love you for this.

54:03.950 --> 54:06.753
Polly, this sweet-big
brother of Brad's

54:06.819 --> 54:09.021
has insisted upon paying
for your hat.

54:09.088 --> 54:11.591
- But he mustn't do that.
- But he has.

54:11.658 --> 54:14.694
- But I couldn't.
- But you must.

54:16.128 --> 54:19.098
That looks adorable
on her, doesn't it?

54:19.165 --> 54:21.067
Doesn't it?

54:21.133 --> 54:23.770
Yes, now all you need
is a corsage.

54:23.836 --> 54:25.972
'I think lilies of the valley
and gardenias.'

54:26.038 --> 54:27.974
I guess I'll need orchids.

54:28.040 --> 54:29.809
- Shall we send out for some?
- Yes.

54:29.876 --> 54:33.613
Let's be going. I must get
a 4:00 train to Boston.

54:33.680 --> 54:38.017
I'm very sorry, Mr. Bradford.
I can't leave without a corsage.

54:38.084 --> 54:41.120
I wouldn't let Polly. I couldn't
let her go out that way.

54:41.187 --> 54:43.923
We'll buy you
a corsage on the way.

54:43.990 --> 54:46.926
- But let's hurry.
- Isn't he a darling?

54:46.993 --> 54:49.528
You're just so generous.

54:49.596 --> 54:51.964
[door buzzer]

54:52.031 --> 54:54.400
Polly, I wonder if
you would answer that.

54:54.466 --> 54:56.603
I'm going to powder my nose.

54:59.271 --> 55:02.241
- Well, what's this?
- Well..

55:02.308 --> 55:05.311
Looks like another hat.
We have a hat, my lad.

55:05.377 --> 55:07.580
- But I was--
- Must have the wrong address.

55:07.647 --> 55:09.248
Oh, no.

55:09.315 --> 55:12.518
- Who's the hat for?
- A Miss Trixie Lorraine.

55:12.585 --> 55:15.955
It's for Trixie.
Let me see it.

55:17.724 --> 55:20.660
Look, isn't this ducky? Look.

55:23.996 --> 55:26.332
- How much?
- It's somewhere..

55:26.398 --> 55:28.100
Let me see the bill.

55:28.167 --> 55:30.136
Bill. Yes, sir.

55:32.438 --> 55:35.675
Seventy five dollars.
Do all hats cost $75?

55:35.742 --> 55:39.511
Now, you dear, sweet man. You
aren't going to pay for that.

55:39.578 --> 55:41.981
Trixie. Come on in, Trixie.

55:42.048 --> 55:45.618
I'm very much afraid
I haven't the change.

55:45.685 --> 55:47.620
- How much do you need?
- Five dollars.

55:47.687 --> 55:50.056
You just keep that.
Buy yourself a yacht.

55:50.122 --> 55:53.192
Oh, but I get so seasick.

55:53.259 --> 55:56.996
- Well, thanks.
- Trixie, Trixie.

55:57.797 --> 55:59.365
Did you call me, Polly?

55:59.431 --> 56:02.201
Isn't this darling?
Handsome bought it for you.

56:02.268 --> 56:06.272
Aw, you sweet lamb.

56:06.338 --> 56:08.808
He shouldn't have paid for it.

56:08.875 --> 56:12.611
Oh, dear. Now he'll
think I'm extravagant.

56:12.679 --> 56:16.716
Oh-h-h, but what a pretty hat.

56:16.783 --> 56:18.818
You do like me in it, don't you?

56:18.885 --> 56:21.654
I think we ought to take
a stroll on Fifth Avenue

56:21.721 --> 56:23.690
and look at the shops.

56:23.756 --> 56:25.892
You'd know how reasonable things
are these days

56:25.958 --> 56:27.960
Come on, J. Lawrence.

56:37.069 --> 56:40.840
- Oh-h-h, ha ha ha.
- Ha ha ha.

56:40.907 --> 56:42.675
I'm a busy man, Ms. Parker.

56:42.742 --> 56:44.176
I cannot afford to waste time

56:44.243 --> 56:46.112
in coming to an understanding
with you.

56:46.178 --> 56:49.448
I've been wanting
to ask you a question.

56:49.515 --> 56:51.450
Are your eyes hazel?

56:51.517 --> 56:54.053
- My eyes?
- Uh-hm.

56:54.120 --> 56:56.723
- Please, Ms. Parker.
- They are hazel.

56:56.789 --> 57:02.061
And such nice eyes.
Such a good, kind expression.

57:02.128 --> 57:05.264
- Ms. Parker, please.
- Now don't be so formal.

57:05.331 --> 57:07.767
Didn't you promise
to call me Polly?

57:08.868 --> 57:10.837
- Polly.
- Thanks.

57:11.437 --> 57:12.839
Ha ha ha.

57:16.608 --> 57:18.677
[jazz music]

57:20.179 --> 57:25.117
- I beg your pardon.
- That's alright, Fannykins.

57:25.184 --> 57:27.854
I've got to have
another cigarette.

57:27.920 --> 57:30.890
Platinum. M-m-m.

57:36.395 --> 57:38.064
Oh. Hello, everybody.

57:38.130 --> 57:41.133
Get her. Just when I was
beginning to have a good time.

57:41.200 --> 57:44.336
- Introduce me, won't you?
- I thought you'd left.

57:44.403 --> 57:46.839
- Ms. Fortune, Mr. Bradford.
- How do you do?

57:46.906 --> 57:48.908
- Charmed.
- You didn't introduce me.

57:48.975 --> 57:51.110
Ms. Fortune,
this is Mr. Peabody.

57:51.177 --> 57:54.747
- Oh, Mr. Peabody.
- Ms. Fortune.

57:54.814 --> 57:56.282
My good fortune.

57:56.348 --> 57:59.585
My good man, are you
by any chance punning?

57:59.651 --> 58:01.253
I'm quite a punster.

58:01.320 --> 58:05.491
I suppose you were a stroke
on your college punsing team.

58:05.557 --> 58:09.796
That's funny. That's very funny.
Ms. Fortune, won't you join us?

58:09.862 --> 58:11.831
I'd love to.
I'm just in the mood.

58:11.898 --> 58:15.067
- Some champagne?
- Indeed, doctor recommends it.

58:16.735 --> 58:18.938
- Did you have a mother?
- What?

58:19.005 --> 58:23.042
- Whose name was Eunice?
- No, I don't think so.

58:23.109 --> 58:26.612
I did have a mother.
Whose name was Gertrude.

58:26.678 --> 58:30.649
- You look like Eunice.
- You do look like Eunice.

58:30.716 --> 58:32.551
- Ouch!
- What's the matter?

58:32.618 --> 58:35.387
Fay has an attack of chiseling.
It's chronic with her.

58:35.454 --> 58:38.557
Another look at him with bedroom
eyes and I'll break your leg.

58:38.624 --> 58:42.795
Excuse me for whispering. Fay
and I have so much in common.

58:42.862 --> 58:45.397
Can we have some more champagne?

58:45.464 --> 58:46.999
A quart.

59:00.046 --> 59:03.015
(Lawrence)
'Now I tell you, there's only
one thing to do.'

59:03.082 --> 59:05.151
We've got to spend
more time here.

59:05.217 --> 59:07.153
We've got to see more of her.

59:07.219 --> 59:10.056
I don't wish to see
any more of her.

59:10.122 --> 59:12.691
What I've seen convinces me.

59:12.758 --> 59:14.526
We absolutely
must make her think

59:14.593 --> 59:17.529
we're an easy proposition.
Suckers, you might say.

59:17.596 --> 59:19.899
'What are you
shaking your head for?'

59:19.966 --> 59:22.902
I'm thinking of
the consequences.

59:22.969 --> 59:27.206
I can make this girl transfer
her affection from him to me.

59:28.374 --> 59:32.011
- What?
- Don't misunderstand me.

59:32.078 --> 59:36.748
Nothing personal in it.
This girl is smart.

59:36.815 --> 59:40.386
Now what are you shaking
your head for? Are you afraid?

59:41.988 --> 59:45.391
- Afraid of what?
- I confess I'm a little afraid.

59:48.327 --> 59:53.499
That girl is very fascinating.
But we're not boys, are we?

59:53.565 --> 59:57.103
- Well, hardly.
- We're men, aren't we?

59:57.169 --> 01:00:00.072
And we needn't succumb
to that sort of feminine allure.

01:00:00.139 --> 01:00:02.808
- Need we?
- Indeed, we needn't. Need we?

01:00:02.875 --> 01:00:07.746
Just because they want something
we don't have to give in, do we?

01:00:07.813 --> 01:00:10.082
No. Not at all.

01:00:10.149 --> 01:00:14.120
- Let me have a light, please.
- A light? Certainly.

01:00:16.222 --> 01:00:17.924
A light?

01:00:17.990 --> 01:00:20.359
Yes, yes.

01:00:24.964 --> 01:00:27.666
Where's your lighter?

01:00:27.733 --> 01:00:31.337
My lighter? Oh?

01:00:36.408 --> 01:00:39.845
(Polly)
'Where'd you get
the lighter?'

01:00:39.912 --> 01:00:41.447
Fanny gave it to me.

01:00:41.513 --> 01:00:44.583
Fanny? This is marvelous.
This is wonderful.

01:00:44.650 --> 01:00:46.919
- Who's Fanny?
- Fanny is Faneuil H. Peabody.

01:00:46.986 --> 01:00:49.021
The kind of man
I've been looking for.

01:00:49.088 --> 01:00:51.023
Lots of money and no resistance.

01:00:51.090 --> 01:00:53.859
Old Peabody's the family lawyer.
This is great.

01:00:53.926 --> 01:00:55.594
Well, I don't think
it's so funny.

01:00:55.661 --> 01:00:57.796
We must tell Brad's brother
the truth.

01:00:57.863 --> 01:00:59.131
The truth about what?

01:00:59.198 --> 01:01:01.033
The truth about Carol
not being me.

01:01:01.100 --> 01:01:03.269
Oh, no, you've
got to go on with it.

01:01:03.335 --> 01:01:06.105
He thinks he's pretty darn
smart. Take him for a ride.

01:01:06.172 --> 01:01:08.774
You said it.
Let's go on playing this game.

01:01:08.840 --> 01:01:10.142
Gee, it's for prizes.

01:01:10.209 --> 01:01:13.012
Look what I got already.
Gold, platinum, animals.

01:01:13.079 --> 01:01:18.050
That's nothing compared to
what I'm getting out of Fanny.

01:01:18.117 --> 01:01:21.920
I don't think it's right. It's
going to cause more trouble.

01:01:21.988 --> 01:01:24.356
Hey, listen. I could do
something that'd make him

01:01:24.423 --> 01:01:27.426
come to Polly on his knees
and beg her to marry Brad.

01:01:27.493 --> 01:01:29.095
- I've got an idea.
- That's right.

01:01:29.161 --> 01:01:30.862
"Use well before shaking."

01:01:30.929 --> 01:01:32.999
We're going to have
unnecessary trouble.

01:01:33.065 --> 01:01:35.534
But I'd marry Polly
with or without his consent.

01:01:35.601 --> 01:01:39.605
- I want to get even with him.
- I want a chauffeur with a car.

01:01:39.671 --> 01:01:43.042
I want a chauffeur
with buttons and a uniform.

01:01:43.109 --> 01:01:45.611
And I want a dog.

01:01:45.677 --> 01:01:49.081
I want a dog named Fanny.

01:01:51.050 --> 01:01:53.685
(Trixie)
'Buy the little doggie
for Trixie.'

01:01:53.752 --> 01:01:55.321
What do you want the beast for?

01:01:55.387 --> 01:01:57.423
Then I'll have something
to remember you by.

01:01:57.489 --> 01:02:00.292
What name do you wish engraved
on the collar, madam?

01:02:00.359 --> 01:02:01.493
Fanny.

01:02:01.560 --> 01:02:04.463
It's not that kind of a dog.

01:02:04.530 --> 01:02:07.199
His name is Fanny.
It's a pet name.

01:02:09.168 --> 01:02:12.471
Every time I look at my dog,
I'll think of you.

01:02:12.538 --> 01:02:14.340
Then I'll have
two little Fannys.

01:02:14.406 --> 01:02:16.575
Here, hold him while
I powder my nose.

01:02:55.381 --> 01:02:58.884
- Shall we dance?
- Certainly. Why not?

01:02:58.950 --> 01:03:00.686
I thought this was my dance.

01:03:00.752 --> 01:03:04.223
Sorry, Bob. Why don't you dance
with this nice young lady?

01:03:04.290 --> 01:03:06.425
Thanks. I'll dance
with whom I please.

01:03:09.961 --> 01:03:12.798
- Shall we indulge?
- Why sure, what can I lose?

01:03:16.168 --> 01:03:18.637
My brother's jealous.

01:03:18.704 --> 01:03:21.006
He has no reason to be.

01:03:21.073 --> 01:03:23.309
I am not prepared to say that.

01:03:23.375 --> 01:03:25.344
Well, then, I'll say it for you.

01:03:25.411 --> 01:03:28.680
You're as light
as a heifer, a feather.

01:03:30.749 --> 01:03:32.684
You know.

01:03:34.653 --> 01:03:38.190
I'm much more the sort
of man for you, Polly.

01:03:39.125 --> 01:03:41.327
Yes, you have your good points.

01:03:42.961 --> 01:03:44.430
Let's dance, honey.

01:03:44.496 --> 01:03:47.266
Don't look at me that way.
He may see you.

01:03:50.669 --> 01:03:53.905
Am I registering jealousy
or am I not?

01:03:53.972 --> 01:03:56.108
No, you're wonderful.

01:03:58.310 --> 01:04:00.612
Watch it. Look jealous.
Here they come.

01:04:06.285 --> 01:04:08.354
Come on, honey.
Let's dance.

01:04:08.420 --> 01:04:11.390
I bet you think it's bolder
dancing this way.

01:04:11.457 --> 01:04:13.592
I think it's delightful.

01:04:19.665 --> 01:04:22.801
- I'm a clumsy soul.
- You're a dear.

01:04:22.868 --> 01:04:24.970
- I'm getting old.
- Aren't we all?

01:04:25.036 --> 01:04:27.038
Say, I'm a little bit
old myself.

01:04:27.105 --> 01:04:31.177
You, old? Why you're the very
personification of youth.

01:04:31.243 --> 01:04:35.147
Oh, thanks, but honest, I don't
know what's the matter with me.

01:04:35.214 --> 01:04:40.018
I have a yen for a little house
in the country, and the fireside

01:04:40.085 --> 01:04:42.921
and carpet slippers
for the old man.

01:04:42.988 --> 01:04:46.792
- Who's the old man?
- You'd run if I told you.

01:04:46.858 --> 01:04:50.829
Ah, I couldn't run
very far. I'm very fat.

01:04:50.896 --> 01:04:53.365
Say, can you imagine me
getting sentimental?

01:04:53.432 --> 01:04:56.602
The most hard boiled dame
on the Dirty White Way.

01:04:56.668 --> 01:04:59.871
You're not hard boiled.
That's just on the surface.

01:04:59.938 --> 01:05:01.240
Underneath, you're--

01:05:01.307 --> 01:05:03.742
Say, what do you know
about me underneath?

01:05:03.809 --> 01:05:05.143
Aha, I mean--

01:05:05.211 --> 01:05:07.613
Oh, I know what you mean,
you old sugar.

01:05:07.679 --> 01:05:11.317
You watch out. I'm falling
in love with you.

01:05:11.383 --> 01:05:15.621
Hello, boy,
when love comes at my age--

01:05:15.687 --> 01:05:16.855
Guess who?

01:05:16.922 --> 01:05:19.725
- It's little Fay.
- Yeah, yeah.

01:05:19.791 --> 01:05:22.428
It's little phooey.

01:05:22.494 --> 01:05:25.931
Oh, Fay, darling,
I have something to show you.

01:05:25.997 --> 01:05:29.335
- Will you excuse us, please?
- Surely, surely.

01:05:29.401 --> 01:05:31.403
- Can you see that?
- See what?

01:05:31.470 --> 01:05:33.071
Read where it says exit?

01:05:33.138 --> 01:05:34.406
- Exit?
- You said it.

01:05:34.473 --> 01:05:36.041
You start walking
and keep walking.

01:05:36.107 --> 01:05:39.311
If you ever come near him again
I'll break both your legs.

01:05:39.378 --> 01:05:41.112
- I could resent that.
- You scram.

01:05:41.179 --> 01:05:42.248
[screaming]

01:05:42.314 --> 01:05:43.815
Did little Fay cry out?

01:05:43.882 --> 01:05:46.685
No, no, that must've been
the cornet you heard.

01:05:46.752 --> 01:05:48.420
[giggles]

01:05:57.629 --> 01:05:59.798
Pardon me, but I think
this is my dance.

01:05:59.865 --> 01:06:02.934
- Oh, I'm so sorry.
- Hm-m, quite alright.

01:06:03.001 --> 01:06:05.604
[slow music]

01:06:31.229 --> 01:06:33.198
Beautiful, isn't it?

01:06:33.265 --> 01:06:36.067
Yes, beautiful.

01:06:36.134 --> 01:06:39.938
You know, I've been watching
you and wondering..

01:06:41.473 --> 01:06:44.643
...you're so obviously
a girl of breeding.

01:06:46.211 --> 01:06:49.114
- Who are your people?
- My father?

01:06:49.180 --> 01:06:53.051
'My father was an official
in the government service.'

01:06:53.118 --> 01:06:54.986
Her father was a letter carrier.

01:06:55.053 --> 01:06:58.290
Mother...mother was an invalid.

01:06:58.357 --> 01:07:00.359
Her mother could have
licked John L. Sullivan.

01:07:00.426 --> 01:07:02.561
Then how did it happen?

01:07:04.195 --> 01:07:06.465
What are you doing
in this theater?

01:07:06.532 --> 01:07:10.569
Well, you see, it was like this.

01:07:10.636 --> 01:07:15.507
I was at finishing school
when my parents died.

01:07:15.574 --> 01:07:18.276
- And they left me--
- An orphan.

01:07:18.344 --> 01:07:20.946
Yes, an orphan.

01:07:21.012 --> 01:07:24.883
I had to find something
to do, earn money.

01:07:24.950 --> 01:07:29.120
And all I could find was...
well, you see?

01:07:29.187 --> 01:07:31.690
I do see.

01:07:31.757 --> 01:07:34.726
You're the sort
of child who...the sort

01:07:34.793 --> 01:07:41.299
of girl who...not cheap,
not vulgar.

01:07:41.367 --> 01:07:44.770
Not at all like people
in the theater.

01:07:44.836 --> 01:07:47.639
'You know, you are
the girl my brother'

01:07:47.706 --> 01:07:50.041
'should be interested in.'

01:07:52.478 --> 01:07:54.312
- Well, I don't like that.
- Neither do I.

01:07:54.380 --> 01:07:57.282
So we're all too vulgar
for J. Lawrence Bradford.

01:07:57.349 --> 01:07:58.517
No. Not at all.

01:07:58.584 --> 01:08:00.352
All except
this nice little girl.

01:08:00.419 --> 01:08:03.355
- I'm too cheap and vulgar.
- No. I didn't mean that.

01:08:03.422 --> 01:08:07.058
I'm going home. I'm not going to
stay and be insulted like this.

01:08:11.329 --> 01:08:12.864
(Lawrence)
'Polly.'

01:08:12.931 --> 01:08:14.800
- 'Polly, you are--'
- I'm getting lonesome.

01:08:14.866 --> 01:08:18.737
No, Polly, you misunderstood me.
I think you're..

01:08:18.804 --> 01:08:21.407
(Trixie)
'Here I am, honey.'

01:08:25.511 --> 01:08:27.912
[door opens]

01:08:29.147 --> 01:08:33.719
You know I-I want
to make you understand

01:08:33.785 --> 01:08:37.523
I-I wouldn't offend you
for anything in the world.

01:08:37.589 --> 01:08:39.290
Oh, let's forget it.

01:08:39.357 --> 01:08:41.493
How about another drink?

01:08:52.303 --> 01:08:53.904
Here.

01:08:53.971 --> 01:08:55.707
I'll forgive you.

01:08:55.774 --> 01:08:57.709
Bottoms up.

01:08:59.210 --> 01:09:02.113
[slow music]

01:09:02.180 --> 01:09:06.317
I want to say...about you--

01:09:06.384 --> 01:09:08.620
Like me?

01:09:08.687 --> 01:09:10.622
Like isn't the word.

01:09:10.689 --> 01:09:13.124
[slow music continues]

01:09:21.966 --> 01:09:24.569
It goes deeper than that, Polly.

01:09:32.010 --> 01:09:34.613
I don't understand it myself.

01:09:35.881 --> 01:09:39.149
- I love you, Polly.
- You're drunk.

01:09:39.216 --> 01:09:41.787
- No, I'm not--
- Yes, you are. You're drunk.

01:09:44.622 --> 01:09:46.825
I love you, Polly.

01:09:53.631 --> 01:09:55.567
You don't mean a word
you're saying.

01:09:55.634 --> 01:09:59.538
You're just playing, aren't you?
I am, you know.

01:09:59.605 --> 01:10:01.473
Oh, stop it.

01:10:01.540 --> 01:10:03.642
[slow music continues]

01:10:27.098 --> 01:10:29.034
Oh, you are drunk.

01:10:30.368 --> 01:10:32.871
[door knocking]

01:10:32.938 --> 01:10:35.674
- Who is it?
- 'It's me, Trixie.'

01:10:39.711 --> 01:10:41.146
- Where's your key?
- Here it is.

01:10:41.212 --> 01:10:43.649
I can't manage it,
my fingers are frostbitten.

01:10:43.715 --> 01:10:44.950
Where'd you leave Fanny?

01:10:45.016 --> 01:10:48.219
I left Fanny behind.
He's waiting.

01:10:48.286 --> 01:10:51.156
Well, what's the matter
with him, sleeping sickness?

01:10:51.222 --> 01:10:52.724
He passed out.

01:10:52.791 --> 01:10:56.027
He doesn't have to pass out
all over our lounge.

01:11:01.900 --> 01:11:05.103
- Say.
- Say what?

01:11:05.170 --> 01:11:07.873
Have I an idea?
Ask me, "Have I an idea?"

01:11:07.939 --> 01:11:10.275
- Have you an idea?
- Listen.

01:11:10.341 --> 01:11:12.944
- We'll stick him into your bed.
- Oh, no, you don't.

01:11:13.011 --> 01:11:15.280
Don't get excited.
You'll sleep with me.

01:11:15.346 --> 01:11:18.516
When he wakes up
in the morning, will he be

01:11:18.584 --> 01:11:21.486
where we want him?
Will he do what we want?

01:11:21.553 --> 01:11:22.921
- Will he?
- I don't like it.

01:11:22.988 --> 01:11:25.791
- You want to get even with him?
- Yes, I do.

01:11:25.857 --> 01:11:27.425
Can't you see, when he wakes up

01:11:27.492 --> 01:11:30.228
what will he ask himself?
What would anyone ask himself?

01:11:30.295 --> 01:11:33.364
"What happened? What am I doing
in this girl's bed?"

01:11:33.431 --> 01:11:37.803
And how many answers
are there to that? You tell me.

01:11:37.869 --> 01:11:39.738
Oh, but nothing
will have happened.

01:11:39.805 --> 01:11:41.807
Of course not,
nothing will have happened.

01:11:41.873 --> 01:11:43.709
- You said it.
- But he'll think.

01:11:43.775 --> 01:11:45.176
You know what he'll feel like?

01:11:45.243 --> 01:11:47.813
He'll feel like, what do
they call them? A cad.

01:11:47.879 --> 01:11:49.615
- I'll do it.
- You take his head.

01:11:49.681 --> 01:11:53.284
You take his head, I'll take his
feet. Don't want to look at him.

01:11:53.351 --> 01:11:56.354
You know, I thought you were
getting kind of stuck on him.

01:11:56.421 --> 01:11:59.725
Don't be stupid, Trixie. I was
just putting on a good act.

01:11:59.791 --> 01:12:02.160
A very good act.
You certainly fooled me.

01:12:02.227 --> 01:12:05.764
(Trixie)
Okay, dearie,
here you go to bed.

01:12:07.599 --> 01:12:10.636
There, now, my little man.

01:12:10.702 --> 01:12:13.271
If you think I've fallen for
that apple-cheeked boyfriend

01:12:13.338 --> 01:12:14.940
I've been chiseling.

01:12:15.006 --> 01:12:17.943
Say, you'd be surprised
what plans I have for him.

01:12:18.009 --> 01:12:20.912
And will he be surprised.

01:12:20.979 --> 01:12:24.349
Say, I'm going to take him
like Graham took Waterloo

01:12:24.415 --> 01:12:25.817
or whatever he took.

01:12:25.884 --> 01:12:30.722
* And when he wakes up
in the morning *

01:12:30.789 --> 01:12:34.159
* When he wakes up in the mo.. *

01:12:34.225 --> 01:12:35.460
Hey, what's this?

01:12:35.526 --> 01:12:37.696
- Ah, It can't be. It isn't--
- It is.

01:12:37.763 --> 01:12:38.964
How did he get there?

01:12:39.030 --> 01:12:40.999
He passed out,
so we tucked him in.

01:12:41.066 --> 01:12:42.801
This is wonderful.
This is marvelous.

01:12:42.868 --> 01:12:44.870
Well, I'm afraid
we've gone too far.

01:12:44.936 --> 01:12:46.204
- Gone too far?
- Yes.

01:12:46.271 --> 01:12:48.206
Oh, no, this is only
the beginning.

01:12:48.273 --> 01:12:50.441
I have to run.
I've something to attend.

01:12:50.508 --> 01:12:53.011
I'll be back in an hour.

01:12:53.078 --> 01:12:57.749
So, my dear brother, you'll cut
off my income, will you?

01:12:57.816 --> 01:13:00.051
Won't let me marry Polly,
will you?

01:13:00.118 --> 01:13:02.954
Well, listen, old fellow,
you don't know it yet.

01:13:03.021 --> 01:13:06.624
But you're going to wake up
a kinder and a wiser man.

01:13:07.826 --> 01:13:10.128
[slow music]

01:14:07.853 --> 01:14:09.387
(Trixie)
'Good morning.'

01:14:10.856 --> 01:14:13.224
- Good morning.
- How would you like your eggs?

01:14:13.291 --> 01:14:15.226
'Where do you think
you're going?'

01:14:15.293 --> 01:14:18.063
'Think you can do
what you did and get away?'

01:14:18.129 --> 01:14:20.498
Ruin a young girl's future
just because she loves you?

01:14:20.565 --> 01:14:23.234
I don't know where I am,
or what you're saying.

01:14:23.301 --> 01:14:25.737
That's too bad.
I'll tell you where you are.

01:14:25.804 --> 01:14:28.406
Oh, I know where I am, alright.

01:14:28.473 --> 01:14:33.011
I mean, figuratively speaking,
I'm confused, I..

01:14:33.078 --> 01:14:36.347
- I don't know what happened.
- Well, I do.

01:14:36.414 --> 01:14:39.284
Plenty, brother, plenty.

01:14:41.686 --> 01:14:46.157
Ah, tell me, now what do
you want me to do?

01:14:46.224 --> 01:14:48.093
Sit down.

01:14:49.460 --> 01:14:52.864
- How much is it worth to you?
- Worth? What for?

01:14:52.931 --> 01:14:54.933
Call it payment
for a night's lodging.

01:14:55.000 --> 01:14:56.868
Well, you don't mean it.

01:14:56.935 --> 01:14:58.669
- Polly doesn't know that--
- Hey, listen.

01:14:58.736 --> 01:15:00.872
What do you think Polly is?

01:15:02.073 --> 01:15:04.209
Oh, I never would
have believed it.

01:15:05.510 --> 01:15:07.846
But why not?
What else could I expect?

01:15:07.913 --> 01:15:10.115
You said it. What else?

01:15:12.550 --> 01:15:15.353
I know what you need, a pen.

01:15:23.161 --> 01:15:25.096
Five thousand,
is that satisfactory?

01:15:25.163 --> 01:15:27.532
What do you think this is,
the Mills Hotel?

01:15:29.935 --> 01:15:31.970
Ten thousand, then.

01:15:33.839 --> 01:15:35.373
And that's all I'll do.

01:15:35.440 --> 01:15:38.176
Well, don't feel generous.
It's not so much.

01:15:38.243 --> 01:15:40.545
- That's your opinion.
- Ah, the pen?

01:15:42.047 --> 01:15:44.816
Now, have you any objection
if I go on my way?

01:15:44.883 --> 01:15:47.986
Objections? Let me open
the door for you.

01:15:51.756 --> 01:15:53.091
Thank you.

01:15:53.158 --> 01:15:55.360
Come back when you
can't stay so long.

01:15:59.797 --> 01:16:02.968
Yay, I've got it. Oh.

01:16:03.034 --> 01:16:05.570
- Got what?
- Rest your eyes on that.

01:16:08.073 --> 01:16:09.875
What's the matter,
isn't it enough?

01:16:09.941 --> 01:16:11.309
I don't want any of it.

01:16:11.376 --> 01:16:13.411
What's the matter with you?
I knew it.

01:16:13.478 --> 01:16:16.247
You are carrying the torch
for that Back Bay codfish.

01:16:16.314 --> 01:16:18.416
Oh, I'm not.
I hate him.

01:16:18.483 --> 01:16:21.519
Sure you do. Why he's got
no more feelings than a hyena.

01:16:21.586 --> 01:16:23.955
He has, too. Don't you talk
that way about him.

01:16:24.022 --> 01:16:27.225
'We've just been playing him
for a sucker. He's a chump.'

01:16:27.292 --> 01:16:29.995
He's not a chump.
He's kind, and he's good.

01:16:30.061 --> 01:16:33.865
Sure, you hate him, alright.

01:16:33.932 --> 01:16:36.868
Oh, no, I don't. I love him.

01:16:36.935 --> 01:16:39.871
Oh, I've never felt
so happy in all my life.

01:16:45.210 --> 01:16:48.279
I've-I've got
a confession to make.

01:16:52.817 --> 01:16:54.085
Well?

01:16:55.486 --> 01:16:57.422
Well, I..

01:17:09.400 --> 01:17:14.539
Last night, I told
Ms. Lorraine...Trixie

01:17:14.605 --> 01:17:16.741
that I cared for her, deeply.

01:17:16.807 --> 01:17:19.577
'And she admitted
an equal affection for me.'

01:17:21.379 --> 01:17:25.816
First time in my life,
true love, real love

01:17:25.883 --> 01:17:27.452
'with a real woman.'

01:17:32.523 --> 01:17:33.524
Look.

01:17:34.592 --> 01:17:36.527
Look at that.

01:17:55.846 --> 01:17:59.217
- I've been tricked.
- You certainly have.

01:18:00.551 --> 01:18:02.087
That's the girl.

01:18:02.153 --> 01:18:04.956
That's the girl Robert
planned to marry all along.

01:18:05.023 --> 01:18:07.025
The one I intended
to save him from.

01:18:07.092 --> 01:18:10.996
No doubt about it. They've
certainly made a fool of you.

01:18:14.299 --> 01:18:16.534
- Oh, what about you?
- Who, me? Well, I..

01:18:16.601 --> 01:18:19.570
Did you know? If you knew,
why didn't you tell me?

01:18:21.272 --> 01:18:24.075
What do you think
I brought you along for, anyway?

01:18:25.576 --> 01:18:30.015
To heave ponderous, ridiculous
sighs at that giraffe?

01:18:30.081 --> 01:18:32.583
Who are you calling
a giraffe, sir?

01:18:32.650 --> 01:18:34.986
I've a suspicion
it's the woman I love.

01:18:35.053 --> 01:18:37.555
You love.
You give me a pain.

01:18:38.689 --> 01:18:40.458
You're coming along with me.

01:18:40.525 --> 01:18:42.893
I'll show them I'm not such
an easy mark.

01:18:42.960 --> 01:18:45.130
- Where to?
- To that woman's house.

01:18:45.196 --> 01:18:47.965
The one who posed
as Polly Parker, who led me on.

01:18:48.033 --> 01:18:50.068
I'm not going with you. I can't.

01:18:50.135 --> 01:18:52.237
- Why?
- Well.

01:18:52.303 --> 01:18:56.474
I have a-a dinner engagement.
A conference.

01:18:56.541 --> 01:19:00.611
Alright, I'll go by myself.
But I'll show her.

01:19:01.879 --> 01:19:04.249
I never said your brother
wanted to marry me

01:19:04.315 --> 01:19:06.284
and I never said
my name is Polly.

01:19:06.351 --> 01:19:09.520
- I took that for granted.
- You take too much for granted.

01:19:09.587 --> 01:19:11.456
I'll ask you to return my check.

01:19:11.522 --> 01:19:14.659
Your check? That's on exhibition
over there on the wall.

01:19:18.496 --> 01:19:21.066
I knew you'd probably
stop payment on it.

01:19:27.638 --> 01:19:29.274
I'll take the necessary steps--

01:19:29.340 --> 01:19:32.110
You'll do what? Listen, you made
a sap out of yourself.

01:19:32.177 --> 01:19:34.345
You tried to make
a sap out of me.

01:19:34.412 --> 01:19:36.714
I never want
to see you again, understand?

01:19:36.781 --> 01:19:39.150
And as for your check,
well, you don't think

01:19:39.217 --> 01:19:41.786
I hold myself as cheaply
as all that, do you?

01:19:41.852 --> 01:19:43.554
Cheaply? $10,000?

01:19:43.621 --> 01:19:45.790
Well, that's your estimate
of me, not mine.

01:19:45.856 --> 01:19:47.592
That check is framed,
not cashed.

01:19:47.658 --> 01:19:50.861
I put it there to remind me
never to get mixed up

01:19:50.928 --> 01:19:52.497
with your kind again.

01:19:52.563 --> 01:19:54.932
Now get out, will you
please? Get out.

01:19:54.999 --> 01:19:56.367
No, I will not get out.

01:19:56.434 --> 01:19:57.835
- You must.
- No, I will not.

01:19:57.902 --> 01:20:00.738
Not until I've told you
what I think of you.

01:20:00.805 --> 01:20:02.673
Don't you dare.
Get out.

01:20:02.740 --> 01:20:04.742
[instrumental music]

01:20:04.809 --> 01:20:07.612
I was drunk the last time.
I'm not now.

01:20:07.678 --> 01:20:11.249
I mean it.
I love you, Polly.

01:20:11.316 --> 01:20:14.819
- My name's not Polly.
- Whatever your name is.

01:20:14.885 --> 01:20:19.056
Carol, that's my name.
Cheap and vulgar Carol.

01:20:19.124 --> 01:20:20.491
Daughter of a Brooklyn
saloon keeper

01:20:20.558 --> 01:20:22.327
and a woman who took in washing.

01:20:22.393 --> 01:20:26.097
Carol, torch singer at Coney
Island. Cheap and vulgar.

01:20:26.164 --> 01:20:28.133
Every time you say
cheap and vulgar

01:20:28.199 --> 01:20:30.135
I'm going to kiss you.

01:20:30.201 --> 01:20:32.670
Cheap and vulgar.

01:20:32.737 --> 01:20:34.539
Cheap and vulgar.

01:20:34.605 --> 01:20:36.307
Cheap and vulgar.

01:20:36.374 --> 01:20:38.443
[instrumental music]

01:20:44.282 --> 01:20:46.651
I didn't mean to fall
in love with you.

01:20:46.717 --> 01:20:48.419
I was only playing a game.

01:20:48.486 --> 01:20:51.122
I didn't mean to fall
in love with you, either.

01:20:51.189 --> 01:20:54.925
I was trying to play
a little game myself.

01:20:54.992 --> 01:20:57.395
You're going to forgive
Brad and Polly, aren't you?

01:20:57.462 --> 01:20:59.697
- No, I'm not.
- Oh, but you must.

01:20:59.764 --> 01:21:01.366
- If they're married--
- Oh, they are.

01:21:01.432 --> 01:21:03.201
They phoned me
from the city hall.

01:21:03.268 --> 01:21:04.902
I'll have
their marriage annulled.

01:21:04.969 --> 01:21:07.738
- Oh, but you said--
- I don't care what I said.

01:21:07.805 --> 01:21:10.275
I was confused, upset.

01:21:10.341 --> 01:21:13.211
Well, maybe
you're confused about us.

01:21:13.278 --> 01:21:15.380
No, that's one thing
I'm sure about.

01:21:15.446 --> 01:21:18.183
But their marriage is off,
definitely off.

01:21:18.249 --> 01:21:20.518
Well, then so is ours.

01:21:20.585 --> 01:21:23.588
- You mean you won't marry me?
- I certainly do.

01:21:23.654 --> 01:21:25.556
- Oh, I'm late. The show. Sorry.
- Polly--

01:21:25.623 --> 01:21:27.625
- 'See you later.'
- Carol.

01:21:27.692 --> 01:21:30.628
'You haven't told me. We've got
to settle this, Carol.'

